\section{Interpretation and limitations}
The scan output can show striking regularities; however, interpretation requires discipline:
\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Anchoring is a convention.} An anchor triple fixes offsets and can shift which integer triples appear ``simple.''
We therefore report the anchor explicitly and keep it fixed across runs unless stated.
\item \textbf{Multiplicity matters.} A good best-fit is not compelling if thousands of solutions exist in the same bounds at the same tolerance.
Any claim must therefore include uniqueness/multiplicity diagnostics.
\item \textbf{Running and scheme dependence.} Quark masses and electroweak parameters depend on scale and renormalization scheme.
A robust regularity should persist under reasonable choices of inputs (within uncertainties) and updated PDG values.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Falsifiability and preregistration rules}
To prevent post-hoc tuning, we adopt the following rules for future work:
\begin{itemize}
\item Fix scan bounds and tolerance \emph{before} looking at new targets.
\item Report \emph{all} solutions within tolerance (or at least the multiplicity and the full set of distinct $q$ values).
\item Treat any parameter change (bounds, tolerance, anchor choice) as a new experiment and report it as such.
\end{itemize}

\section{Next steps}
Immediate technical next steps for the repo (not claims about physics):
\begin{enumerate}
\item Replace placeholder PDFs with generated plots from the scan outputs.
\item Emit CSV tables under \texttt{data/derived/} and build LaTeX tables from those deterministically.
\item Extend the analysis to CKM/PMNS phases (handled in later papers) under identical reproducibility constraints.
\end{enumerate}

